I live in a small town in Michigan, far from any big cities. There are farms all around, and small towns that visitors like to see. We do not have large stores or many restaurants. We must drive everywhere we want to go.

Still, I live in one of the most beautiful places in America. My town sits between two large lakes - Lake Michigan and Lake Charlevoix. You can find places to swim everywhere you look.

My area shows what small-town life is like. The houses are not close together. Each house looks different and many are old. Some owners have made their houses look new again. Most houses have rooms under the ground that you can see from the street. The houses are painted in many colors. Most have big yards where children play. Some people grow plants for food or keep animals.

The people who live here work hard. Many are raising children or have grown children who moved away. You can see children playing in the streets. People walk their dogs or ride bikes. Everyone knows their neighbors. When someone does not belong here, people notice. Neighbors wave to each other and smile.

People take good care of their yards. They cut their grass and keep their plants neat. While the houses are not fancy, this is a good place for families. It is quiet and safe.

Near my house, you can walk to many places. There is a building where police work, a place for health care, and a place to take things to be made new again. There are fields where people play ball games. Small planes fly from a nearby airport. Children can walk to get ice cream or ride bikes to the park. The center of town is not far away.

This is a very good place to live.

I live in a planned community in the outer part of a city. All the houses look very much alike because a group of owners makes rules about how everything should look. When you enter our area, you see many similar houses with small green areas in front. Each house has stones for decoration, a short drive for cars, and sometimes small trees. Every house has space for two cars inside.

The roads are very good because they are new and well-kept. Most houses have one floor, but some have two floors. We do not have mail boxes in front of each house. Instead, we have many mail boxes together at the end of each street, like you might see at an apartment building. We need a key to get our mail. There are also two bigger boxes for larger items that come in the mail.

Because we are far from the center of the city, we have much space. We have several swimming pools that anyone who lives here can use. The pools have gates around them. We also have paths where people can walk their dogs or just walk for exercise. The area is so big that you can run here without going to a special place for exercise.

Most people who live here have stopped working because they are older. Some younger working people live here too. It is very safe, and people watch out for each other. The city is big when you think about how many people live here, but it feels small. We have one shopping center. It is not very big, but it works well for us. I must drive about fifteen minutes to get to stores, but then I can find many different places to buy things. We have expensive food stores with special healthy food, and we have cheap stores with fewer things to buy.

My area is safe and well-kept, like many other places where people live today. We have good things like pools and walking paths. While stores are not very close, we can drive to any store we want to go to.

I first learned about my home while listening to a radio show about missing people. This surprised me. Most homes in this area cost more than one thousand dollars each month to live in. I had never heard this story before, and neither had my friends.

Life can be hard here. Some of my friends cry at night because things cost so much money. We have learned to live with less. We buy things from places that sell used items. The smell of old books and clothes becomes normal. As you grow older, you notice these smells less. 

There are three stores near me that sell used items. I can walk to them all. There is also a library and two shops that sell old books and interesting things. Many cars and people fill the streets each morning, but inside these stores, it is very quiet. It is a good place to spend time.

The city is growing bigger. A large computer shopping company has its main office here. This makes me think of New York City. Everyone has their own plans, and no one asks much from others. You can be by yourself, and people will not bother you. It is different from the South, where people often want to know about your life.

I live with good neighbors. One plays the piano, and two like to sing. We help each other and share food. We celebrate happy times together and help when someone is sad. We bring each other's mail. Even though this is a big city where people can feel alone, my neighbors make it feel like home.

Though I live in a very large city with tall buildings everywhere, the people around me make it feel warm and friendly. Because of them, I know I made the right choice to live here.

I live in a small town in the middle part of America, near a big city. I live on the east side of town, where many people do not have much money. The houses here cost less, and most people rent them or bought them at low prices. Still, it is a nice place. People who live near me are friendly and say hello when I walk by.

While crime happens a bit more here than in other parts of town, it is still mostly safe. There have been some bad events near my home in the past ten years, including some shootings. Our neighbors lost their son last year when he was shot near a local bar. My family has been lucky, though we sometimes lose small things from our front steps if we forget to bring them inside.

Like many places in America, our town has problems with dangerous drugs. Many people have died from these drugs. But there are places here that help people who use drugs, and there are classes to teach people how to save someone who takes too many drugs.

Even with these problems, there are many good things about my town. My son goes to a very good school. The teachers and workers there are wonderful. Even though my son has special needs, other children are kind to him, and he is very happy there. Parents and teachers work together to make the school better. Because many families in our town do not have much money, all children get free food at school.

The town leaders have made the town look nicer by fixing roads and parks. But most of this work happens in the middle of town and on the west side, where the stores are. The east side, where I live, does not get as much attention, and this makes people in my area unhappy.

Still, I like living here. People are nice, the schools are good, and there are enough stores to buy what we need. Our house is not worth much money, but it is comfortable and good enough for us. We have lived here for more than 16 years, and we want to stay here.

I live in a special part of the city called Hilltop. It sits on high ground, with many old buildings that tell stories from the past. My home is in a tall building across from an old theater. Down the street, there is a place where people play games and meet friends on warm nights. Many people wait in line to enter this place during summer evenings.

Near my home is a city park. It is big, with concrete walls and wide steps around it. In winter, people without homes put their tents on these steps and nearby sidewalks. Though it does not snow much here, the rain makes life hard for them. They stay close to each other in the middle of town to stay warm. They can also walk or take a bus to a place where they can wash.

What makes this area special is not just the old buildings or the way the hills go down to the sea. It is the people who live here that make it special. Years ago, Hilltop was known for having problems with groups that broke the law. Even now, people tell stories about how government workers tried to make the streets safer.

The people here work hard to keep their area clean and safe. Some say white people should not walk here at night, but I think this idea comes from old fears. Maybe it is because I look like I might be from here, or because I understand the hard things people face, but I feel at home.

This place has shown me much kindness. People have given me warm clothes when I was cold. Shop owners have helped me when I needed it. Even on the darkest nights, strangers have stopped to help me and tell me I matter. No matter where I go, Hilltop will always be my home.

I came to live in this area when I was ready to start my last year of middle school. At first, it was not easy to find friends, but I became close to two boys who lived near my house. They have moved away now, but I still remember our time together. Most of the same people who lived here when I came still live here today.

My area looks like many other places where Americans live outside big cities. Most houses have two floors. When the weather is warm, I can hear children playing outside. Most days are quiet here. I have never had trouble with anyone who lives nearby. People leave you alone unless you need help. When I get things sent to my house, no one takes them. I feel safe with my neighbors.

There is a small park very close to my house. I have many good memories there. I played many games there with other boys, like basketball and football. Once, I hurt my nose playing football, but that was the only bad thing that happened. Now, I take my young cousins to play there. They love the swings and slides. When I tell them we are going to the park, they get very happy. The park makes me think of many good times in my life.

Many different kinds of people live here. You can find food from all over the world nearby. There are places that serve food from China, India, Mexico, and Italy. Many people now use their phones to have food brought to their homes. There are also many fast food places and pizza shops.

You can find everything you need in the stores here. There are places to clean clothes, two drug stores, and a big food store. There is even a store that sells Indian food and things to make Indian meals at home.

I really like living in this area. When I see stories about bad neighbors on the internet or news, I am very happy with my neighbors.

I live near my college, which makes me happy. My area has many apartment buildings and some places to eat and drink. These places do not cost too much money. One place where people drink recently got a new name. It costs more now, but it is still fine.

Most people here are nice. Many are students or people who do not have much money, as the apartments are not expensive. There are many children because a school is close by. I do not know the people who live next to me, and that is fine. They smoke a lot, so the building owners put something in the hall to make the air smell better. My friend and I think this is funny.

The buildings here are old, but some look better inside. New apartments were built down the street, but they were not built well. They cost too much money because they are close to school.

There is a cheap place to eat five minutes away. They use paper plates and heat most food in a small oven. Next to it is a place to buy gas. The city made the street better last summer. Now there is a good path to walk on and green grass on the sides.

Many trees grow near my building. They cut some down, but many still stand. Behind my building are more apartments. I live on one street, but the next street is not as nice. The walking path there is broken, and the buildings do not look good. More bad things happen there, but some bad things happen on my street too.

I like where I live. I can pay for it, and everything I need is close. I can walk to school, and I can take a bus to buy food or go to the city center.

I live in a special group of houses. Each house is actually two homes joined together. They are placed with space between them, so they look like single homes. All of them are yellow with white front areas and green metal tops. Most people who live here are friends. In the evening, we often meet and talk while children play with their toys or draw on the ground. It feels like going back to an earlier time, away from today's world of computers.

Trees and fields are all around us, with blue sky and white clouds above. The only bad thing is the strong storms we get. Last night, we heard warning sounds that told us a dangerous storm was coming. I went to hide in my bathroom with my small dog, some soft things to sit on, and my bag. My big dog stayed in the living room, making loud sounds because he was afraid.

The only noise outside was the sound of ice falling from the sky. After the storm, steam came up from the road because the weather got much cooler very fast. Then the sun came out while it was still raining, and two colorful lines appeared in the sky. I took pictures to show my friends.

After an hour, people came back outside. Mothers watched their children play while food was cooking. I am new here, having moved from the north to the south. I like how people talk here with their special way of speaking. My home has two rooms for sleeping and two rooms for washing. Though the houses look the same outside, they are different inside.

I enjoy walking in the big field behind my home. There is a small lake there, but we cannot swim in it. I see deer sometimes, and in the morning, I hear big frogs making noise. I live forty minutes from the big city of Charlotte. Every morning, I hear farm animals making noise. It feels like living in a small town. We can even hear a donkey making sounds in the evening from a nearby farm. I am very happy I found this nice place to live.

I have lived in my neighborhood for ten years, and I want to share my story. When I first moved here, I was very sad. We moved from Riverdale to Stockbridge because my parents wanted a better life for me and my little sister. They chose this area because it had better houses and schools.

Over time, I made new friends at school. I did not know many neighbors, except for Mr. Glen and Dennis, who live next door. They became like family to us. I remember going to Mr. Glen's wedding with my family. It was a very happy day. At the wedding, I caught the small white band that Mr. Glen's new wife, Ms. Veda, threw from her leg. We danced and had fun with their daughter, Marsharii, though I have not seen her since then.

Our neighborhood is like a maze, but now I use my GPS to find my way around. I often spent time with my friends Kason and Curtis playing video games. I also like going to the park to enjoy nature, which helps me feel calm and peaceful. I practice my balance there with sticks I bought from the store, and sometimes I bring my wooden practice sword.

The park has places to play basketball and tennis. I have not played these sports in a long time, but it is good to know they are there. My father used to teach me and my best friend how to play tennis with Mr. Graves. They made us work hard, but we had fun.

I have many good memories in this neighborhood. These are just some of the stories that mean the most to me. I believe even better things will happen in the future.

I live in a small town called Johnston in South Carolina. Our town is special because we grow many peaches. In fact, we call ourselves the Peach Capital of the World, and this is written on our welcome sign.

Most of our land is used for farming. People grow peaches or raise cows. The houses outside town are far apart from each other. Many have metal roofs to stay cool in the hot summer. These homes sit back from the road, leaving space in front for animals or growing food.

In the center of town, we have one traffic light where four roads meet. This is where you find our stores. We have three places to eat: a Chinese food place run by one family, a Mexican restaurant, and a burger place called Gary's. We also have a small drug store known for its special cola drinks, and one food store called IGA. Because IGA is expensive, many people drive to a bigger store in another town.

Our most popular store is Dollar General, which sells many everyday things. We have a furniture store that will bring items to your home, and next to it is a place where people can take their pets for care. The town has one doctor's office and one animal doctor's office, both small but good at helping people.

Johnston has one school for young children. Older students must go to school in another town. We do not have a park yet, but the town is building one that will be quite big. There are no movie theaters or many places for fun activities. Still, Johnston is a nice place to live, even though it is so small you might miss it when driving through.

I live in a small town in Tennessee. My house is on a street that connects two main roads. Cars often pass by, but our area is mostly quiet. Most people stay in their homes for many years, so we know our neighbors well.

People here work in their yards and do daily tasks. In winter, children ride sleds down a nearby hill. Our house sits at the corner of the street, so we can see who comes and goes. We know which cars belong here, and we notice when we see new ones.

Some neighbors walk for exercise or with their dogs. Children ride bikes in the street. My family stays home a lot because we work here. There are four of us - me, my wife, and two daughters who are eleven and fourteen years old.

We play outside, even when it rains. Sometimes we cook food on our back deck. The smell of cooking food fills the air. From spring to fall, someone is always cutting grass. You can hear lawn machines almost every day.

Many trees grow in our area because it was once woods. The trees give us shade, but they drop many leaves in fall. We must gather leaves and burn them each year. I like how burning leaves smell. Recently, winters have been warm, so it feels like fall lasts longer.

Our car house is behind our home, so we rarely use the front door. When I work on my truck in the car house with the doors open, I feel more connected to the neighborhood.

During special days like Thanksgiving, Christmas, and Mother's Day, people visit their families. Many cars park on our street then. I enjoy living here. If fewer cars used our street as a path to other places, it would be perfect.

I live in the high desert where there is mostly brown earth everywhere you look. Green grass is rare here because water costs too much. When I first came here in the 1990s, houses were far apart. Now there are more houses, but they are still spread out. Our area is growing like a city, which is happening in many places.

Most people here are friendly. Like all cities, some areas are better than others. In my area, I live near kind older people. The stores here are mostly common chain stores. We do not have expensive stores nearby. If you want those, you must drive far.

Many people here work in building houses and buildings. This is because our city still has much empty land to build on. This worries me because I like how things are now. I moved away from a big city and do not want to live in one again. I work in building too, putting up walls and ceilings.

What I really like about my home is the animals. People come to the high desert to see its simple beauty. The weather and land here create special places where different animals live. People who live here should learn about these animals so we can live together safely.

My family enjoys the desert life. My three children love to watch lizards and desert insects. Right now, they are outside trying to catch some to look at them.

Our city, Victorville, has some interesting places to visit. The San Bernardino County Fair comes every year and is fun for families. Near us is Wrightwood, where people can see snow and learn winter sports. The Victor Valley Museum shows rocks, old bones, Native American items, and things that tell the story of how our city grew.

My neighborhood is different from what most people would describe. While many people live in their own houses, I live on a college campus. My main community is my dormitory, and the wider campus is also part of my neighborhood.

Even though this is unusual, my neighborhood has many things that normal neighborhoods have. There are places to live, people, stores, and a park.

There are three kinds of places where people live here. First, there are apartments where two to four people share a room. Each building has two floors with four to six rooms on each floor. About twenty people live in each apartment building. Second, there are regular houses that people who work at or graduated from the school can rent. These houses have two to four bedrooms, but there are not many of them. Third, there are dormitories, which are the most common. In these buildings, two students usually share one room, and hundreds of students live in each building.

The people in my neighborhood come from many different places and cultures. Teachers and workers often live in the houses. New students live in the dormitories, and older students usually live in the apartments.

My neighborhood has many stores and a park. You can find places to eat, buy clothes, and get food from grocery stores. Everything we need is here in our neighborhood. The park is a place where everyone can spend time outside. Everyone helps keep it clean and safe.

I live in a place with few walking paths. My house is at the top of a very steep hill. Many people who exercise like to run up this hill. Since there are no walking paths, people must walk on the road. The road has holes and can be dangerous to drive on.

The power lines above look old and broken. It rains a lot here, and falling tree parts often break the power lines. Workers must fix them often, making them look strange.

There are many tall green trees here. But people do not like these trees because they block the view of the water. That is why houses are built high on the hill. They have big glass windows on their upper floors to see the water. When the sun goes down, the water looks beautiful and bright, and the sky turns orange. But most days are cloudy, so the sun looks soft through the clouds. The weather is usually wet, and green plant growth covers everything. Once, my car turned green after sitting still for a month.

Not many young people live here, even though there is a school nearby. Most people who live here are older and do not work anymore. Instead of children, people have many dogs. The dogs often sit in yards or run in the streets. Sometimes they even come into houses if doors are left open. This happened to me once.

Many rabbits live here too. They are big and dig holes in people's gardens. My cats catch many of them. We also see many birds: small ones, very tiny fast ones, and big hunting birds. But the black birds chase the big birds away.

There are no stores near my house. But if you walk down to the water, you can eat at places that serve fresh fish. There is not much sand by the water, but people like to throw rocks into it. The water is not very wide. You can see the other side even when it is cloudy.

Bensonhurst is a part of Brooklyn that is easy to find. You can get there using public transportation, which many people in New York City use. The area feels like a city neighborhood.

When you visit, you will see many Asian stores. In the past twenty years, many Asian people have moved to Bensonhurst. You can find Asian-owned stores on almost every street. There are many food stores and places to wash clothes. Local people like these stores because the food is good, prices are low, and the stores are close to their homes. Near my house, there are four Asian food stores within a short walk.

The area has people from many different places. Many are new to America or have parents who came from other countries. While many businesses are Asian-owned, there is also a nice park nearby. The park has basketball courts, a field for sports, places to play handball, and areas for children to play. In summer, children can play in water fountains. People from different backgrounds play together well in the park.

Most people live in two-family houses. There are also some big buildings where people can buy homes. The people are friendly, but the area can be noisy. Cars often play loud music and make noise with their engines.

At night, you should be careful. While the area is mostly safe, some people might cause trouble. There have been cases of stealing and bullying. Also, even though there are rules about cleaning up after dogs, some people do not follow them. You might see dog waste on the streets when walking to the train or stores.

Despite these problems, Bensonhurst is still a good place to visit. Just be aware of your surroundings and watch where you step!

Let me tell you about Portland, Oregon. This city is different from most places in America. On a building in the city, there are big words that say "Keep Portland Different." This building has many uses - people can eat pizza there, drink alcohol, watch music shows, and see dancers.

Some people want Portland to stay like it was twenty years ago, when fewer people lived here and things cost less money. Other people come here because they want to be different and know that people will accept them.

Many rich people from California are moving here, and new buildings are going up everywhere. Still, Portland remains special. The city is not always friendly to everyone, but it welcomes people who might not fit in other places.

We have normal things too. Like everyone else in America, we buy things made in other countries. We have people who do yoga, young people who dress in special ways, and people who work in offices. Maybe we just do not take these things as seriously as others do.

In my part of the city, houses are painted in bright colors. People grow flowers and food in their front yards. In warm weather, people put boxes on the street with free things inside. These boxes often have clothes and books, but sometimes you can find special things you did not expect.

Portland has problems too. Some people use drugs, and many people do not have homes. The rain and dark clouds for much of the year can make people feel sad. The city tries to help people who need it, but like other places in America, we cannot help everyone who needs help.

Portland is full of different kinds of people. Some like to do yoga with small animals called goats. Others love to watch our soccer team play. Some people follow their dreams, while others just talk about their dreams while drinking at bars. We are all different, and that is what makes Portland special.

The mountains stand in the north. They watch the sun rise and set each day. Even when I am too busy with work to notice them, they remain strong and steady. On hard days when I feel worried, the mountains catch my eye. Looking at them helps calm my mind and gives me strength to continue.

I came here for college. The mountains near the school were the first thing that caught my attention. The school itself is beautiful, with nice buildings and small lakes with trees. But the mountains are special to me.

The town is lovely too. There are many coffee shops where I spent long hours studying. A short bus ride takes you to the old part of town, where red and brown bricks cover the walls of restaurants and offices. This area feels as busy as a big city. But walk past the library, and you find quiet streets again. Having both busy and quiet places so close makes this town special, like it wants you to discover its secrets.

I have many happy memories here. I remember walking with friends by the old park swings after staying up all night. I remember running to catch free movies at the nice theater downtown. But sad memories live here too. I often sat by the small lakes late at night, thinking about life while watching turtles and ducks swim. Sometimes I cried there, wondering about my place in the world.

One day, I walked past the lake, through the quiet streets with small houses, until I reached a main road. The sun was rising, making the palm trees shine. I looked up and saw I was walking north. There they were - the mountains, touching the blue and yellow morning sky. Without words, they reminded me to stay strong.

Most people might miss it at first. Behind the shopping area, there is a special place where many people live. If you walk past the old, empty food store and the hotels that are mostly quiet all year, you will find a busy neighborhood.

On these streets, there are several apartment buildings. They stand next to each other like boxes in a row. The first building has had some problems, so we will not talk about it much. But the other buildings next to it are different and special. Most people who live in this area do not know about them.

Across the street, there is a small college. Students come early in the morning with their coffee. They enter through big metal gates while people in cars wait, sometimes not very happily.

The street meets another street where there is a park on one side and a medical building on the other. The medical building has chairs outside and a fan that moves the warm summer air. At the park, children play in the grass while bees fly around the flowers. Older people walk their dogs on the path. They do not like the young people on skateboards but they smile at the young girls who talk about boys near the playground.

Near the park, there are some stores together in a row. There is a place that sells fish and rice, a store for swimming things, and a place where people get their fingers and toes painted. There is also a place that sells cold, sweet ice cream. Young people often buy ice cream there and then go back to the park to ride their skateboards.

This neighborhood is like many other American places. It is in the quiet south where things stay the same for a long time.

I want to tell you about where I live. The houses in my area are mostly for one family. Some houses have been made into two homes that share walls. My house has a small green space in front and a place for cars on the left side.

The houses here make people think about past times when many Americans wanted to live away from big cities. That dream is not as strong now, but our area shows it is still alive.

People here are not as happy as before. The small yards are not as nice as they used to be. Still, every home has cars, and children play in the streets as if nothing else matters. The school, which is almost 100 years old, still teaches children and makes older people remember their young days.

There are not many churches now, and few people go to them. But many young people still play basketball. Each house looks different, but they all feel like home. We have a big food store run by a family from Yemen - they may be the only Arab family here. Most people living here are African American.

The streets are wide. Children play ball games and move only when cars need to pass. Many families have lived here for many years. They tell stories about times when everyone knew their neighbors.

We once had a place that taught fighting sports, but it is now a drug store. We have a small movie house that shows old films for less money. Young people do not go there much, but older people like it.

A big road passes near our town, but you cannot get on it here. Young people wanted a way to get on the road from our town, but older people said no. They thought it would hurt our town.

They are building a new school for older students. We need to pick an animal or thing to represent our town. I think we should choose something that shows both old and new ways of life.

I live in a big city where many different kinds of people live close to each other. Houses are mixed with places where people work and shop. There are many offices, stores, eating places, and places where people go to have fun. You can always find new places to eat or buy things.

Some stores are part of big companies that everyone knows. Small stores owned by local people are becoming more popular too. These stores are in shopping centers and along the streets. You can walk to many of them from the quiet areas where people live.

There are parks nearby where families take their children to play. Many different groups of people live in my area. We have gay people, Jewish people who follow their old ways, and people who came here from Russia and nearby countries. If you go a little further, you can find areas where Chinese, Korean, and Armenian people live together.

Getting around the city is hard. A ten-mile trip can take two hours when there are many cars on the road. Most people drive cars because the city is too big to walk everywhere. It is hard to find places to park your car.

Workers are building many new tall buildings where people can live. While many people want to move here, those who already live here worry about more cars on the roads. Not everyone lives in tall buildings, though. Some people live in big houses, some in small houses, and others in small apartment buildings.

People of all ages live here. I do not know many of my neighbors well. When I was young, I played outside with the children who lived next door, but now people do not spend as much time with their neighbors.

"What do you see here?" she asked as we drove past the corn fields that went as far as we could see. "This is all there is!" I said. I knew she would be surprised by how empty it looked. She grew up where stores were close to her home. She had never seen so much open land before.

I told her about growing up in Ohio's countryside. As I shared my story, she began to understand who I was and where I came from. If you drive down a small road, you will find a water-filled hole in the ground. My neighborhood is just past it. The houses are made of brick and have large yards that people keep very clean. In spring, there are many flowers and trees that change with each season.

Nice cars sit in the driveways, shining in the sun after being washed. Near my gray house lives my friend from Korea. He spends much time cutting his grass and singing. Everyone smiles when they see him. He used to be a doctor, but now he is older and moves more slowly. He rides his grass-cutting machine most days.

At my house, birds walk in the yard while our small dog runs after them. Behind the house, there is a small stream that flows to the water hole. You can hear frogs and cows from nearby farms. Across a wooden bridge we built, there is an area full of trees and wild plants. I spent much of my young life there. I built places to play in trees and ran after animals. Friends from nearby would often join me.

The cold times are hard but very pretty. The green yard turns white and empty. Trees that had bright flowers become bare. When snow falls, everything looks magical. My younger sister made snow shapes on the ground and snow people. We often played in the snow, throwing snow balls at each other. We built snow houses with sticks to hide behind. In our special place, we played and did not worry about anything else. We were just children having fun.

original_texts:
I live in Rural America, specifically small town Michigan. Where you go from farmland to small tourist cities. There is no big city malls, no Wal-mart, Target, or even an Applebee’s. Anywhere you need to go, you have to drive to get to. Despite that I live in one of the most beautiful places in the world surrounded by water. My “city” is surrounded by water. Beautiful Lake Michigan to one side, and Lake Charlevoix on the other. Everywhere you go you can find a beach to dip your toes in. My neighborhood, reflects the idea of small town. Houses are not stacked upon one another. They aren’t cookie cutter houses that are built the same. They are older homes, some of them being updated and remodeled some of them being older. Most homes have basements. Full Basements that you can see from the road. Many houses in the neighborhood have older aluminum siding. We have houses every color you can imagine in the blocks that surround my house. Most of the houses have yards. Yards with trampolines, and playsets. Some people have gardens, and fences for their animals. The houses resemble Middle America. Hard working people who work to make a living and are either raising families or have raised families. On any given day you will see kids running up and down the streets. You will also see people walking dogs, biking and rollerblading. Neighbors know neighbors and you can recognize who fits in and who doesn’t belong. You will see someone grilling outside and wave, or even someone that is walking their dog from a few blocks down and smile pleasantly. The lawns are kept in decent condition. Nobody has leaves piled up from fall time. Green grass is kept mowed and under control. If people have plants and bushes in their yards they are kept trimmed down. It isn’t a beautiful neighborhood that you drive into and think wow look at the nice homes, but one you drive into and think you can tell this would be a good place to raise a family. It’s quiet, peaceful and, and safe. While only average looking, it is exceptional for the fact that it represents what people want in the world, which is a safe place to land at the end of the day. Within walking distance there is the county sheriff’s department and jail. The Health department is just next to that. The city recycling center sits just down the road, and neighbors and residents from around the city utilize the services they provide. We have baseball and softball fields nearby where you can hear the announcers keeping score and calling the names of players. Our small town airport is next to that. You can be playing outside, or even inside and hear the rumbles of small engine planes taking off and landing. You can walk to get ice cream from the local ice cream place, and if you are really into it you can make it downtown from our neighborhood of homes. My kids can ride their bikes to the park which is only 8 blocks or so away. It is a really great place to live.
The general area in which I live in can be described as your typical cookie cutter suburbia. For my neighborhood in particular, the presence of a homeowner's association is very apparent. Upon entering, you'll see nothing but well-maintained single family homes, which we can thank the homeowner's association for. The front yards are all very similar. There's a small patch of landscaped grass, some decorative pebbles, and rather short driveways. Every so often you'll see small trees as well. Everyone has a two car garage. As you continue to drive along throughout the neighborhood you'll see newly paved concrete. Despite many different families living here, the roads are in excellent condition. You won't find any potholes or anything like that here. Most of the houses are single story, but sometimes you'll see two stories as well. We don't have a typical mailbox set-up that you would expect for single family homes. There are no individual mailboxes in front of each house. Instead, it's more like apartments where there are a large grouping of mailboxes at the end of the street. Everyone uses a key to gain access their specific mailbox. And there's two larger lockers for packages. Again, you can thank the HOA and their obsession with uniformity for this. The location of my house is on the extreme edge of the nearby city, so my neighborhood can be described as part rural, part suburbs. As a result, we have a lot of land for, well, everything. There's multiple community pools to which anyone living here can access. It's well maintained and gated. And then there are various walking trails where you can walk your dog, or just go for an evening stroll by yourself. You don't have to visit a park to get your exercise in. The neighborhood is large enough that you can simply run around it and get more than enough exercise. Most of the community is made up of retired people. It's a very safe area, and everyone looks out for one another. Mixed in with that, we have a small amount of middle aged and young professionals too. In regards to the city, it's surprisingly large - at least by population - but also has a small time town feel. We have the vast majority of amenities that you come to expect and rely on. For example, we have a exactly one mall. It's not huge, but it gets the job done. For me, it takes around 15 minutes of driving to get anywhere significant, but once I do that, I am greeted with many different stores to choose from. We have everything from high end grocery stores where you can get organic food, to bargain outlets that only stock a small selection of items and has bare minimum staff to keep costs down. All in all, my neighborhood is safe, well-maintained, and pretty typical. We have a lot of nice things, like pools and walking trails. And although we aren't right next door to any sort of shopping, you can just hop in a car and go to any major chain that you'd like.
The first time I'd heard of my place, I was listening to a podcast about people who'd gone missing. It was a little surprising. Almost every apartment in the area was going for over a thousand dollars a month. I'd never heard anything about that story and neither had any of my friends. Maybe it's the struggle. I know a few of my friends cry themselves to sleep at night. Things are expensive, but we've learned how to be frugal over the years. You start to like the dusty smell of flea market toys and mothballed clothes. You smell a lot less in adulthood. You might start to smoke, or you might just be too accustomed to the state of things. But the flea market always asserts itself. The smell of adulthood is dusty magazines stacked on a closed piano. It wedges itself in the leather and stays in even after you wash it. Here, there're 3 thrift stores in walking distance. If you start on the far side, you can patronize two charity thrifts, a library, a rare book store, and a curio shop. Downtown is dense, cars and people fill the streets every morning, but you'd never hear it in the thrifts. No matter how many people or cars pass by, the store is silent. It's a nice place to lose an afternoon. Every year, there's more and more of those. Cars and people flood it. It's a developing city, they say. Headquartering one of the largest online empires for e-commerce and delivery, it's still showing growing pains. It reminds me of New York. Everything and everyone is set on their own goals, and there isn't a whole lot anyone asks from you. You can be alone, quiet, and independent, and people will leave you alone. It's not like the South, where being a little concerned means you care. You don't pry into anyone's life here, really. You can keep up your shell as long as you'd like, and the city will crash and roll back like waves on the beach. It's a lively place to be. Between the pianist next door and the two amateur vocalists upstairs, there's always something going on. In a way, we have less of an apartment of strangers and more a community of friends. We come together for our needs, celebrate birthdays, mourn funerals, and help each other when we can. In a way, I'm lucky to be here. I quite like most of my neighbors and they treat me pretty well. I try to make sure to clean after myself and leave them food and they do the same in kind. I bring mail to them and they to me. It's nice to see them and I believe they enjoy my presence as much as I do theirs. I live in a massive, dehumanizing modernist sprawl but it's people like my neighbors that make me feel like I didn't totally ruin my life.
I live in a small Midwestern town that is just outside the suburban areas of a major city. My immediate neighborhood, on the east side of the town, could be described as the most economically disadvantaged area of the town. Property values are low, with most houses being rented to or owned by low-income individuals. However, it is not unattractive or unpleasant. My neighbors are generally friendly people who will smile and say hello when I walk down the street. Crime rates, while slightly higher than other parts of town, are still generally low. There have been a few violent crimes in the past ten years within a few blocks of my home, including a few shootings and at least one homicide. Our next door neighbors lost their son in a shooting outside an area bar last year. Fortunately, our family has not been directly affected by crime other than having an occasional item disappear from our porch if we forget to bring it inside. In general, the town in which I live has been profoundly affected by the “opioid epidemic” that has affected many parts of the United States. Many lives have been lost due to fentanyl overdoses. Fortunately, there are many resources in my town to combat this epidemic, including several addiction rehabilitation centers and Narcan training sessions for families and friends of those affected by addiction. Despite these challenges, this town has many positive attributes. My son’s elementary school has excellent staff, from the principal to the teachers and support staff. Despite having special needs, he has not faced any bullying thus far due to the incredibly positive atmosphere of the school, and he loves it there. We have an active PTO that plans multiple events throughout the year to promote family involvement and educational progress. Because over 20% of our town’s population lives below the poverty level, the elementary school provides free breakfast and lunch to all students, so that no child ever has to go hungry. No child or family is treated as “less than” due to an inability to pay, and costs for school fees, supplies, and field trips are very reasonable. The City Council and staff have made many improvements to the appearance of our town, including repaving roads, landscaping, and refurbishing city parks. Unfortunately, most of these improvements have taken place in the center of town and on the west side, where all of the shopping areas are located and most of the traffic passes through. The east side where I live tends to be neglected, which is a point of contention for those in my neighborhood. Overall, I do enjoy living in this town. People are generally friendly, the schools are great, there are enough shopping options (both small businesses and larger retail stores) to meet my family’s needs, and our home may not be worth much, but it is comfortable and adequate. Our family has lived here for over 16 years, and we cannot imagine living anywhere else.
My neighborhood is full of culture. It's set upon a hill, surrounded by buildings with historical meaning. I live in a 7 story apartment building right across from the old live Theater, and a block down The Hill, is this cool little arcade bar that different types of people flock to on warm summer nights. Often times, especially on the weekends in June and July, you will see a line of people waiting to get in. A few blocks up is the nearest city park. It's pretty big considering the part of town it sits in. Encircling the park is concrete, with tall stairs poured into the wall. During the frigid winter months, homeless people set their tents up in neat little rows along the sidewalk and along the wide steps. It doesn't snow much, but it rains, and the torrential down pour in the mid-winter months often tends to make it difficult to keep warm. Setting their tents up close together, in the center of town rather than out in the jungle, keeps them much warmer. They're also within reasonable walking and transit distance to the only family center for miles, where they can bathe and shower. What I love about my city though, isn't the beauty of the historic nature- the tall proud buildings, the architecture that is spattered through-out the varying levels of the hills that roll down towards the ocean. What I love about my neighborhood is the culture of the people themselves. You see, Hilltop once was the most notorious neighborhood on the West Coast for gang violence. You still hear stories, even three decades later, about the federal government officials and the DEA sweeping through like a broom, trying to clean the streets. The people, they don't forget. Stories are still passed from generation to generation, on through to transplants like me, of those days. The people work hard, even though it's still considered one of the rougher 'hoods' in the entire city, to keep it cleaned up. They still care about what goes on in their city, on their block. They say that if you're white, you shouldn't walk around the Hill after dark. Truly, I believe that this warning is reminiscent of the old days, and it is tinged with the sour taste of social conditioning. Perhaps it is that I am just dark enough to pass for a not entirely "white-girl," or maybe Hilltop recognizes me as one of their own, someone who is just as painfully aware of the reminders that constantly plague our nation. Reminders that racism, cultural conditioning, and assumptions are made out of ignorance and fear, even in a city that is supposed to be a cultural melting pot Utopia. I know one thing: no matter how far I roam, the Hilltop is home. I feel alive walking those streets at night, meeting people who have more quickly and rarely nefariously offered me a jacket than to rob me. It's a place where laundromat owners have stayed open just a few minutes later so I could charge my phone when I had no where to escape from the rain. It's a place where I have sat, believe myself to be invisible, huddled against concrete store fronts on the most grey dreary of nights, only to have someone stop and look me in the eye, hand me a $5, and tell me I'm beautiful and valuable.
I moved to this neighborhood just when I was about to start eighth grade. It was hard for me to make friends at first, but I ended up getting close to someone who lives two houses down from me and another guy that lives on my street. Neither of them lives there anymore but the memories are still there. The same people who lived here when I first moved here are still here for the most part. My neighborhood is pretty similar to your average American suburban neighborhood. The neighborhood has a lot of two-story houses in it. Every weekend or just whenever it is warm outside I hear the kids playing outside. The neighborhood is quiet most days of the week. I have never had a problem with any of the people in the neighborhood. You are left alone in this neighborhood unless you need help. I have ordered multiple packages online and have never gotten a package snatched off of my porch. I feel like I can trust my neighbors. There is a park a minute or two away from my house. I have a lot of memories there. I have played basketball, football, and baseball there with the other guys in the neighborhood before. I also ended up with one of my worst memories there when I got elbowed in the nose playing football, but the good memories outweigh the bad. Nowadays, whenever I go to that park it is to spend time with my cousin's kids. They are much younger than me and still like playing on swings and slides and all of that type of stuff. Just the thought of going to the park makes them excited. The park makes me very nostalgic for a number of different reasons now. The neighborhood is very diverse. You will find all kinds of food nearby. In just a one mile radius, you would be able to find Chinese, Indian, Mexican, and Italian restaurants. However, nowadays, a lot of people just use apps just as GrubHub and DoorDash to get their food delivered to them. The most popular food places are the fast food shops but you can get those near pretty much any suburban neighborhood. There are also plenty of pizza places. The stores here contain everything you would ever need. There are multiple dry cleaners nearby. There is a Walgreens and a CVS on the same street as well as a Jewel-Osco grocery store, which is popular in the Midwest. Some of the stores are even diverse as there is an Indian-owned store if you are ever in the mood to make some homemade Indian food or to buy some ready-made Indian food. Overall, I am a fan of my neighborhood. Reading on social media and seeing on the news some of the horror stories other people have to go through with their neighbors makes me grateful for mine.
My neighborhood is nearby to the college that I attend, and for that I quite enjoy living there. There are mostly apartment buildings, but a few restaurants and bars that are fun to go to and aren't terribly expensive to go to. One of the bars was just renamed, and that one is more expensive to go to but it isn't really the worst quality of service or drinks there. Most of the people are nice. They are either college kids or they are lower income, since the apartment housing isn't very expensive. There's a lot of children nearby since there is an elementary school within walking distance of my apartment. I don’t know my neighbors, but I don’t really want to. They smoke a lot of weed and so the management of my building put an air freshener unit right across from their door, which my boyfriend and I found very funny. It’s almost insulting. The buildings that are around me are usually pretty old looking but might have renovated interiors. Down the street a bit there are brand new apartments, but I don’t like them because I know the construction done on them wasn’t particularly good. They’re cheaply built but the rent is expensive, which I think is such a scam but because they’re near campus, the management of those buildings can get away with it. There is a really cheap restaurant about five minutes from where I live that serves food only on paper plates and most of what they make is microwaved. Then across from that is a gas station, which I’ve heard isn’t a very good place to work. But thanks to some money from the city, the road was redone last summer so that there’s a nice big sidewalk, lots of grass on the medians and sides of the roads, and now the area is a little nicer. But the apartment building I live in is shrouded in tress. They cut a few of them down, so there are a few stumps, but there are a lot more trees where I live than down the road. Behind my apartment complex is a tree line and then another set of apartments. I live on 42nd street, but right behind is 43rd street and that one isn’t as nice. The sidewalks are really bad and falling apart, and most of the buildings on it look shabby. There are a lot of trees on this street, but that is probably to hide what the buildings look like. Most of the crime in my area has happened at an apartment complex on that street, but then again, I can’t blame just them. There are apartments across the street from me that also have a lot of crime and a rather transient population. But I think I like where I live. I can afford it, and there’s plenty of useful amenities nearby. I especially like how the university is within walking distance and there are two bus stops so that I can get to the store and downtown with ease.
My neighborhood is made up of duplex's on a cul-de-sac. They are intermittently placed and spaced so that they look like individual houses. The only difference is each is painted yellow with white porches and green metal roofs. Almost everyone, but not all, are friends with each other. We stand at the end of a not pre-decided driveway some evenings and chit chat while the small children of the neighborhood play with their toys, sidewalk chalk or fly their kites. It is very refreshing in this modern all to mechanical/computer filled world. It is rather like stepping back in time. We are surrounded by fields and trees enhanced by blue skies and white billowing clouds. The only downfall? This season, we are experiencing tornado warnings and for the first time, last night we actually heard actual tornado sirens so we had to head towards shelter. Sure enough, you would have found me in my bathtub clutching my littlest dog along with my purse and a few pillows. My big dog wanted nothing to do with the bathroom and remained in the livingroom, nervous and barking, nervous about the odd circumstances. The neighborhood was quiet except for the sound of large hail which fell all bout the ground. After the storm the road literally was steaming from the change of temperature. We went from 92 to 75 in a matter of minutes. The hail immediately melted when it hit the hot pavement. As I looked up towards the clearing skies, the sun came out and it started to rain. A double rainbow apparated. I ran into the house and grabbed my camera. Quickly snapped pictures to share with my Facebook friends and family. They were in awe, as was I. The streets remained quiet for another hour, before some people finally came home from wherever they were when the thunderstorm hit. Then it was business as usual, mom’s and children outside as dinner cooked. Such a friendly neighborhood for this gal who has recently moved form NH to NC. I adore the southern accent that people speak with. I have a two bedroom and two bath apartment, as does everyone. Though all the houses look the same on the outside, not all of the apartments are the same on the inside. Some are actually quite tiny. It doesn’t make sense to me. I love to walk along the biggest field behind where I live and mosey down to the pond that is not made for swimming. I have seen deer and in the morning you can hear the giant bullfrog singing his song. It is a fantastic place to live just forty minutes outside the city of Charlotte. Each morning is welcomed by the sound of roosters crowing from the surrounding farms. It is rather like living in a small community village of it’s own. We even have a donkey at a nearby farm that you can hear braying in the evening to let us know he is there. I was lucky to find this gem of a neighborhood.
Well, considering that I’ve been here for about 10 years, I guess I can share what I know. First off, I was pretty sad when I first came to my neighborhood. I came from Riverdale to Stockbridge, and I’m not going to lie, I cried, because I missed them and I loved them.. but my mom and dad wanted the best for me and my little sister, so we moved to a better location for housing, a better high school, everything was considered “not ghetto” when we moved to our new neighborhood. My neighborhood is a quaint little town. It doesn't stand out from any other in South Carolina, but it's got a significant impact on the agriculture sector. Johnston is known as the Peach Capital of the World, something that the town proudly boasts about on the welcoming sign. It's primarily composed of farmland dominated by either peach trees or cattle. Houses that aren't located within the main part of town are widely spaced apart; most are two stories with either metal roofs to help combat the blazing summer heat or gray shingles. More often than not these houses aren't located near the road, but are further back allowing for the front fields to be used for animals/crops. Within the main part of town, there's a single stop light that hangs at a four way. Here is where the only stores in the entire town are located. There are three places in which you can get "fast food': Hong Kong, a small Chinese restaurant run by a single family, Fiesta Mexican Restaurant, or Gary's, a small burger chain. There used to be a pizzeria, however it closed down a short time ago. There is a very small family-owned pharmacy called Maxwell and Halford Drug; funnily enough, they're best known for the Cherry Coca-Cola they sell. There is a small, but expensive grocery store called Independent Grocers Alliance, more commonly known as IGA. While it is the only grocery store in the entire town, many individuals only stop to pick up one or two items; most prefer to travel to a Walmart in Batesburg-Leesville in order to purchase the majority of their groceries. The most popular store in the entire town is Dollar General; this store sells a vast array of everyday items and it often busy from the moment it opens until closing time! There is a very small furniture store, Possibilities Furniture & More, run by a kind woman who is well-known within the community. The store has been in Johnston for a plethora of years and even employs two movers who will deliver the purchased furniture! Attached to the furniture store building is a small pet groomers called Clark's Cuts and Kennels. They provide a multitude of services such as daycare, boarding, grooming, nail grinding, bathing, etc. Both a doctor's and veterinary practice are situated away from the primary part of town; they are both very small practices, though well-equipped to aid the residents of Johnston. There is a single elementary school called Johnston Elementary School. Once students have completed fifth grade, they must attend both middle and high school in the next town over. There are technically no parks within the town, however they are currently in the midst of creating a 2.5 acre recreational area in order to provide families with more opportunities to enjoy outings and attract more visitors/potential residents. Admittedly there isn't much to do; there are no movie theaters, bowling alleys, "hang out" spots, playgrounds for children, areas to walk pets, or a large variety of restaurants. Despite this it's a nice town, so small that you could pass in the blink of an eye without realizing!
I live in a typical suburb area in a small southern town in Tennessee. It's a connecting street between two state highways, so we get a bit more traffic on the street than I'd like, but other than that, it's a quiet neighborhood. There's not too many folks that move in and out, so I've grown used to most of the people that live in the neighborhood. People busy themselves with yard work and other daily chores for the most part. In the winter, we sled down a hill on our side street. We live in a house at the front corner of our street, so we see everyone coming and going all day long and are familiar with the cars that people drive around here. Whenever we see a strange vehicle, we tend to take note of it. Some of the neighbors go walking for exercise or just to walk their dogs. Kids play on their bikes and all that you would expect from that. We are at home a lot since we work from our house. There are four of us, Myself and my Wife, and two Daughters ages eleven and fourteen. So, I'd say that everyone else is used to us coming and going as well. We get outside and play, sometimes even in the rain. Once in a while we grill outside on our back deck and it's always a pleasant smell from the barbecue and all. It seems that there's always someone cutting grass around here and you can hear a lawn mower nearly every day from March through about October, when the grass finally stops growing. We have a lot of trees in our neighborhood as it was originally a wooded area, so there's lots of shade, but there's always a lot of leaves in the Fall as well. So, that means raking and burning the leaves on a yearly basis. I like the smell of burning leaves too, so that's always a nice sign that Fall has arrived. Lately, we've not been having much Winter to speak of, so it just feels like a long Fall. Our garage is at the back of our house, so we seldom use the front door of our house unless someone knocks on the door, which is rare. I like to work in the garage on my truck or other projects from time to time and when I have the garage doors open, it feels like I'm more tuned into the neighborhood. On holidays it is pretty quiet around here. Thanksgiving sees some of the neighborhood families visiting with people from out of town and there are extra cars parked everywhere during that time of year. It's the same at other holidays like Mother's day and Christmas. All in all, I like living here. If it weren't a through street, it would be perfect.

What I like about my home is the different animals. People come to the high desert for many reasons, not the least of which is the stark beauty of the desert itself. Human residents of the high desert should take the time to learn about the non-human residents who share this environment in order to co-exist safely and harmoniously. My family and I have adapted very well to the wildlife. I have three children and they are all obsessed with lizards and dessert bugs, as I am writing this now they are outside trying to catch different specimens. As far as attractions goes we have some. Interested in the natural history and culture of the high desert ecosystem? When asked to describe my neighborhood, I'm sure that my answer is somewhat unique. While others who respond to this are most likely homeowners with their own individual lives, my situation is a tad bit different. I consider my neighborhood to be the college campus that I stay on, and the people that live in my dormitory to be my community. I also consider the surrounding campus to be my neighborhood, albeit to a lesser extent. Despite this peculiarity, my neighborhood shares some commonalities with the more conventional ideas about a neighborhood. Just like any conventional neighborhood, the neighborhood I stay in has houses, people, stores and parks. Let us begin by discussing the "houses" that comprise my neighborhood. Before I begin to explore the houses in my neighborhood, it would be best to clarify the types of house that can be found in my neighborhood. There are three types of housing in my immediate vicinity, the apartments, the actual houses, and the dormitory houses. First, In the apartments, there are usually between 2-4 people in any given room, and there are about 4-6 rooms on each floor. The most common building type can house about 2 floors, so on average, there are 20 or so people living in each building. Second, are the actual houses that are available for anyone with an affiliation to the school to rent. Typically these are 2-4 bedroom setups that usually have alumni living in them. However, there are only a handful of these types of houses spread throughout the neighborhood, as they are less efficient. Finally, there are the typical dorm rooms which house 100's of students. In these, you have two people sharing a room with some exception, and it is the most common type of housing in my neighborhood. With housing covered we are ready to move on to the people. My school prides itself on diversity and this is reflected in the makeup of my neighborhood. There are people from all cultures and ages that live in my neighborhood. Most of the professional staff live in the houses that are placed in the neighborhood, whereas the newer students stay in the dormitory style housing and the older students stay in the apartment-style housing. The people in this neighborhood can't be done justice by simply talking about them, so it would be best to simply move on to the stores and parks in my neighborhood. Since my school really is it's own self-contained neighborhood, it has a plethora of stores and a single park. The stores are a mix of dining options that would be found in any other neighborhood, and the schools own unique brand of clothing and grocery stores. As such, anything that is needed can be found within my neighborhood's boundaries! Additionally, the park in my neighborhood is a playground for all the diverse people in my neighborhood, it is kept clean and free of crime by all the members of my neighborhood!
There aren't many sidewalks where I live. Everything seems to flow downward, and my house sits right at the crest of the steepest hill in the neighborhood. People call it the "work out hill" because so many joggers like to run up it during their daily work out. As there aren't any sidewalks at all on my street everyone walks on the road. There road is pitted in a few places and can feel a bit hazardous to drive on. Some of the telephone and electric wires strung up around the block at tattered looking. It rains and storms a lot in our area, so branches and other debris often strike down the power lines and the constant repairs make them look checkered and patchwork-y. There's many tall evergreen trees all around everywhere you look. But people here hate the trees. They strive to cut down as many as possible because the trees obstruct the view of the ocean. That's why many of the houses are built so high up on the hill, with huge glass-fronted second stories that loom up one after the other to take in the view of the bay. It's gorgeous around sunset when the water seems to get lit up from below and the sky turns orange. It's cloudy more often than not, though, so you end up seeing most of the sunlight through a haze. Most days are overcast and damp. Moss grows on everything it can: roofs, cars, and railings. I once left my car parked out in my driveway for a month and when I went out to use it, it had turned green and furry with moss. Took me three hours to scrap it all off. There aren't that many children around where I live, though there's a school only a few blocks away. Most of the people in my neighborhood are older, many of them retired. Instead of kids, people have dogs. It's common to see them sitting out in people's lawns or racing down the street after each other. If you leave a door or window open you risk having them sneak into your house. I found one once in my living room and had to shoo it back out the front door. Rabbits run wild around the area. Some of them are good sized, and the gardeners hate them because the dig up the roots of plants and burrow into people's lawns. My cats love them though, and have hunted most of them out of our neighborhood. We also get the usual assortment of birds: small sparrows and hummingbirds, and the occasional hawk or eagle sometimes swoops by until the neighborhood crows chase it off. There aren't any stores around, but if you hike downhill to the waterfront there's a few restaurants that serve fresh seafood. There isn't much of a beach down there, but the rocks along the shore are fun to hurl into the water. The bay itself isn't very wide. You can see the opposite shoreline clearly even through the mist on most days.
